<font color="#FF0000">THE COST WAR </font><br>
<tt>Thu Feb 12  6:16:17 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
It is true that some Vets were spit on. This was not done or supported by the majority of anti-war protesters. It is also true that anti-war protesters were also spit on, and attacked. It was not one sided, nor was it right by either side. <br><br>
As for why, I think that the question of why Vets were looked down on is a long and complicated question that will take books to answer propoerly. I think that some of the answer is that people who were oppossed to the war were often fighting to stop the war for years! Towards the late 60's, there was a feeling that the choices were laid out and that people who went to fight were doing so with some knowledge about the war being wrong and they still went. Therefore it was a conscious decision to partake in doing something wrong or immoral.<br><br>
I think that some people were so pained by the actualities of the war that they were unwilling / unable to hear any of the reality of what went on with people's lives in Vietnam. After years of being bombed with pictures and stories of firefights, napalm, agent orange, bombings etc. they could not take listening to that same reality from someone who was there. That same total hate of the war also spread to a shunning of the Vet. <br><br>
There was an incredable pallor of sorrow that was cast over the U.S. at that time and a matching frustration. Imagine seeing a people and a country being destroyed and you, powerless to stop it. And then you look and see next to you someone who participated in it. It was very hard for people to cross the gap between fighter and protester. It is also true that many people who supported the war, were unable or unwilling to talk to the Vet about their experience. It was a Hi, welcome back lets get back to business as usual and pretend that there is nothing different about you now that you have come home. Denial was often the way that people from all views tried to hide from the hurt of the war.<br><br>
As for their being a hidden part of the war in the minds of those who served....  Of course there is. For one, this WEB site is so special, because people are here talking about and facing things that they have not faced since the war. Because someone fought in the war does not mean they had a clear understanding of the politics of decision making back in the Pentagon or the White House. And don't think that one can only deny something for so long. Some people deny things forever. We have people today who deny that the Holocoust ever happened. <br><br>
Please note two things, You say I want to ask a question of the protesters, why did you spit on the vets... Don't lump us all together, as we cannot lump all Vets together. We (protesters) were made up of all classes and all races, men and women across America. We did what we did for millions of different reasons.  <br>
And also, don't make demi-gods out of the Vets. They are people who did what they did for thousands of reasons. Some were fearless, some fearful, some were wanton killers and others as respectful of life as one could be in that situation, some people went crazy from that experience and others found strength, maturity and wisdom from their trials and  tribulations. <br><br>
As for why the Vet was the 'whipping boy' of the government, that is also a difficult question. In part the govenment had to deal with the constant flow of returning Vets and getting them into the work force. They had no reintegration plans for the Vets and offered no good transition programs to help then return to &quot;normal' life. The government had medical claims from agent orange and PTSD, which they did not want to foot the bill on. If they acknowledged the true damage done to some who fought then they would have to foot the bill. There was also an image being portrayed of Vets coming home and being strong &quot;John Wayne&quot; types. Many Vets came to the US from Vietnam in 24 - 48 hours and were discharged and sent on their way. They were dazed and confused by the abruptness of the transition, their experiences denied or downplayed by Americans of all sides and generally misunderstood. The government wanted to sweep this travisty of justice under the rug.
